<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Grachev Warns of Consequences of Air Strikes </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1802203294 Moscow Russian Television Network in Russian 
1700 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1802203294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Russian Television Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Statement by Defense Minister Pavel Grachev; place and date </F>
not given -- recorded; from the "Vesti" newscast] 
  [Text] A decision to make ground-attack and bombing strikes 
against positions around Sarajevo would, of course, be bound to 
have very unwelcome consequences. In the first place I would 
say: the international prestige of the United Nations would be 
undermined. That is certain. This action would look like a 
unilateral action to punish the Serbs. Moreover, great losses 
among the civilian population are inevitable. 
  Second, the inflicting of these strikes could trigger a 
large-scale war, and, even worse, these strikes could act as a 
trigger for other states, neighboring states, to be drawn into 
this war. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

