<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Does Not Rule Out More Peacekeepers </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2102214694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1851 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2102214694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev today had a 
nearly 40-minute telephone conversation with U.S. Secretary of 
Defense William Perry. As before, the two officials discussed 
the situation in Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  In the course of the conversation, Grachev proposed a 
contingent of U.S. troops be deployed in areas around Sarajevo 
which are predominantly populated by Bosnian Moslems. In his 
opinion, this would further improve the situation, after Russia 
sent its peacekeepers to the positions of Bosnian Serbs. 
  However, the U.S. Secretary of Defense said the United 
States 
did not plan to deploy its troops in these areas. 
  In turn, Grachev proposed deploying contingents of such West 
European states as Great Britain, France and Germany there. 
Perry promised to discuss the proposal with the other defense 
ministers. 
  Grachev said Russia insisted on the unacceptability of NATO 
air strikes on military installations of any of the warring 
sides. 
  In an interview with journalists after the end of the 
conversation, Grachev said Bosnian Serbs had withdrawn the bulk 
of their heavy hardware from around Sarajevo. He said he was 
confident that the Serbs will accurately fulfil all their 
obligations. 
  Grachev did not rule out the possibility that more Russian 
peacekeepers, including the 27th motor rifle division of the 
Privolzhskiy district and the 46th motor rifle division of the 
Leningrad district, might be deployed in the Sarajevo region, if 
necessary. 
  In an answer to journalists' questions, Grachev said NATO 
air 
strikes on Serb positions seemed very unlikely at the moment. 
He suggested that such strikes may be possible only in case of 
provocations, and are the most likely to be dealt on 
sporadically populated highland areas as "retaliation or 
pressure." He pointed out once again that any air strikes in 
the area were unlikely at the moment. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

