<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian, U.S. Delegates to UN Issue Joint Statements </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2102095594 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0804 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2102095594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Boris Sitnikov] </F>
  [Text] United Nations February 21 TASS -- The Russian and 
U.S. chief delegates made joint statements to journalists after 
urgent U.N. Security Council consultations held at the 
initiative of Russia on Sunday evening. 
  U.S. Ambassador to the U.N. Madeleine Albright said that the 
United States has just received good news from Sarajevo. 
Everything looks well for the time being. The U.S. will 
continue to watch very attentively to get convinced in the next 
few days that the NATO ultimatum is being fulfilled. 
  The United States is also very satisfied, Albright 
continued, 
that Russian troops intend to participate in the U.N. Protection 
Force and believes that a role to be played by Russians will be 
very useful. 
  Russian permanent representative to the U.N. Yuliy Vorontsov 
said: "The Russian Federation called for this Security Council 
meeting because it was worried during the day that snow would 
prevent UNPROFOR from taking weapons left by Serbs under its 
control. 
  "It looked at some moment that UNPROFOR cannot find these 
weapons in snow. That was a technical problem which disturbed 
us very much. Then, we received a report from Akashi that he 
intends to take these weapons under UNPROFOR's control, and 
there is no need for air strikes at this stage. This was good 
news." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

