<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev in Athens, Talks With Germany's Kinkel </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1802122594 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1012 
GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1802122594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS special correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Athens, 18 Feb -- Talks between Russian Foreign 
Minister Andrey Kozyrev, who arrived here yesterday, and Klaus 
Kinkel, head of the German foreign policy department, ended in 
the early hours. The parties discussed the development of the 
situation around the Bosnian conflict in connection with the 
positive response to a personal letter from Russian President 
Boris Yeltsin from Serbian President Slobodan Milosevic and 
Radovan Karadjic, leader of the Bosnian Serbs, and also from the 
Bosnian Serb parliament. The point is that the sides agreed to 
withdraw their heavy guns from a 20-km zone after receiving a 
promise that Russian forces would take part in the peace-keeping 
operations in the Sarajevo vicinity. 
  During an intensive dialogue lasting nearly three hours, the 
ministers got in touch by telephone from the residence of the 
German ambassador in Athens, where the talks took place, with 
French Foreign Minister Alain Juppe and U.S. Secretary of State 
Warren Christopher. The parties are aware of the need to 
undertake a joint initiative shortly to advance the process of a 
settlement around Sarajevo and of the Bosnian conflict as a 
whole. 
  In addition to this, the ministers had an in-depth 
discussion 
of the state of Russian-German relations in connection with 
President Boris Yeltsin's forthcoming visit to Germany, 
scheduled for late spring. K. Kinkel invited A. Kozyrev to 
visit Germany in order to prepare for the visit, and the Russian 
foreign minister will go there at the beginning of May. 
  Today sees the start of A. Kozyrev's consultations with the 
European "troika" -- the former, present, and future presidents 
of the Council of the European Union; that is, the foreign 
ministers of Belgium, Greece, and Germany -- and also, in all 
probability, telephone consultations with British Foreign 
Secretary Douglas Hurd and Warren Christopher. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

