<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Discusses Aid to Northern Regions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1802183694 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1110 
GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1802183694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Athens, 18 Feb -- The foreign ministers of Russia 
and the FRG discussed in Athens German assistance to the 
development of the northern regions of the Russian Federation. 
Galina Sidorova, political adviser to the Russian foreign 
minister, told the ITAR-TASS correspondent that one of the 
subjects discussed by A. Kozyrev and K. Kinkel was German 
assistance in the development of contacts with Russia's northern 
regions, in the first place with Murmansk. Germany, as the 
future chairman of the Council of the Economic Community, 
intends to hold a meeting there of the three (the former, the 
current, and the future chairmen of the Council of the European 
Community), to see on the spot what can be done for establishing 
cooperation with Murmansk Oblast. 
  Germany intends to participate most vigorously in the 
development of this oblast and at the meeting of the ministers 
some specific decisions in this area were discussed. In 
particular K. Kinkel intends to propose a German town as a 
"twin-town" for Murmansk. 
  Germany is ahead of many other countries in terms of 
fleshing 
out its political partnership with Russia. If effective 
cooperation is established with Murmansk, this could serve as a 
positive example for other regions of Russia, the minister's 
political adviser pointed out. 
  A. Kozyrev and K. Kinkel also discussed the situation in the 
Baltic region and Russia's attitude to the Baltic states. 

</TEXT>

