<H3> <TI>   Suggests Bosnia Conference Be Held </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1802195994 Moscow Radio Moscow World Service in English 
1900 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD1802195994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Moscow World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In Athens Russia's Foreign Minister, Andrey Kozyrev, 
has suggested that an international conference on Bosnia be held 
some time next week. He said the call was for a conference on 
Bosnia and it came from President Boris Yeltsin. The United 
States, German, British, French, and Greek Governments had 
already been notified. Kozyrev made the statement after he met 
with his Greek, Belgian, and German counterparts in Athens. 
Speaking with newsmen in the Greek capital, he stated Yeltsin's 
call for the Serbs to remove their heavy weapons and the Serbs' 
willingness to meet this call created favorable conditions for a 
peace settlement. The minister said Russian peacekeepers were 
ready to be deployed in Sarajevo and other areas of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. A spokesman for the United Nations has told 
the French news agency 400 troops of the Russian battalion based 
in eastern Croatia have started moving toward Sarajevo. 

</TEXT>

