<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Views `Partnership for Peace' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1902185694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1802 GMT 19 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1902185694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondents] </F>
  [Text] Prague February 19 TASS -- The dispute over NATO 
expansion has lost actuality after the adoption of the 
"Partnership for Peace" programme, according to Russian Foreign 
Minister Andrey Kozyrev. 
  "We believe that the dispute has lost actuality at all. Now 
the 'Partnership for Peace' plan has been adopted and we believe 
that its implementation will give us a lot of work at least for 
the foreseeable future", he told a press conference on Saturday 
after meeting Foreign Minister of the Czech Republic Josef 
Zieleniec. 
  Both Russia and the Czech Republic have to implement the 
plan 
first and then think what to do next, according to Kozyrev. 
  "We believe that NATO is an organisation with which it is 
necessary to cooperate. But NATO is only one of such 
organisations. There are also the European Union, the CIS, the 
Visegrad group. That is why we are discussing how to use all 
these organisations, how to meet the challenges which none of 
them, including NATO and the CSCE, are ready to meet so far", 
Kozyrev said. 
  The Russian minister admitted that certain differences in 
the 
positions of the two sides do exist, but they are caused "not by 
a head-on collision of interests, but rather by the complexity 
of problems which are to be jointly solved." 
  "It was in this spirit that the issues of ensuring European 
security, including the crises in Bosnia and other hot spots, 
were discussed", Kozyrev said. 
  Zieleniec stressed that Russia had met with understanding 
the 
position of the Czech Republic about its integration into 
European structures. 
  He added that remaining bilateral problems, including 
financial issues, would be soon solved and that it is necessary 
to accelerate the preparations of a visit of the prime minister 
of the Czech Republic to Moscow. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

