<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Comments on Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2002203394 Belgrade TANJUG in English 2010 GMT 20 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2002203394 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Prague, Feb 20 (TANJUG) -- Russian Foreign Minister 
Andrey Kozyrev Sunday rejected the possibility that NATO should 
realize its threat to launch air strikes if Bosnian Serbs do not 
withdraw their heavy weapons from around Sarajevo. 
  `We disregard the deadline. We do not take the deadline (set 
by NATO) into account', Kozyrev told the press after a meeting 
with Czech Prime Minister Vaclav Klaus. 
  After accepting the Russian initiative for the deployment of 
Russian peacekeepers between Moslem and Serb forces, Bosnian 
Serbs Friday started withdrawing their heavy artillery from 
around Sarajevo. The operation is being hindered by snow and 
bad weather. 
  Meeting Kozyrev Friday, Czech Foreign Minister Jozef 
Zieleniec said it was important that Russian forces jointed NATO 
lately in establishing peace in Sarajevo [sentence as received]. 
  Kozyrev however underlined that Russian forces in Sarajevo 
can act only under UNPROFOR [UN Protection Force] command, 
adding that the peace conference would be resumed in a few days. 
  Kozyrev Sunday ended a two-day visit to the Czech Republic. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

