<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin, Clinton Discuss Bosnia on Phone </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2002205694 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 2021 
GMT 20 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2002205694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, 20 Feb -- Russian President Boris Yeltsin 
telephoned U.S. President Bill Clinton. Vyacheslav Kostikov, 
the Russian president's press secretary, said that they 
discussed problems pertaining to the situation in 
Bosnia-Herzegovina. 
  As a result of the conversation, an accord was reached on 
postponing bombing, taking into account the recent Russian 
diplomacy. The U.S. President highly assessed Boris Yeltsin's 
political initiative, which made it possible to ease 
significantly the crisis around Sarajevo. 
  In the course of the telephone conversation, it was 
confirmed 
that decisions stemming from the development of the situation 
around Sarajevo would be adopted through UN mediation. It was 
agreed to continue consultations on the settlement of the 
situation in Bosnia in the upcoming days. 

</TEXT>

