<F P=100> INTERREGIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow Talks End in `Protocol for a Cease-Fire' </TI></H3>
<H4>   Date To Be Set Later </H4>
<F P=102> PM2202173194 Moscow PRAVDA in Russian 22 Feb 94 p 2 </F>
<F P=103> PM2202173194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow PRAVDA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Igor Lenskiy report under the rubric "Our Correspondents </F>
Report": "Karabakh: Give Peace a Chance"] 
  [Text] A working meeting in Moscow between V. Sarkisyan 
and M. Mamedov, Armenian and Azerbaijani defense ministers, with 
the mediation of their Russian colleague, General P. Grachev, 
and V. Kazimirov, Russian Federation Foreign Ministry special 
envoy, ended with a protocol on a full cease-fire in the 
Nagorno-Karabakh zone. Nagorno-Karabakh representative B. 
Saakyan also took part in the meeting; he sat separately from 
the state delegations, a fact which symbolizes the autonomous 
participation of the unrecognized Nagorno-Karabakh Republic in 
the conflict. 
  We were told by the Russian Federation Ministry of Defense 
that a definitive date for the cease-fire would be established 
later, following coordination with the political leadership of 
Armenia, Azerbaijan, and Nagorno-Karabakh. According to the 
testimony of an officer from the Russian Federation Ministry of 
Defense, who took part in the talks, the atmosphere was entirely 
amicable. Although the full text of the signed document will 
not be published for certain reasons, the officer made it clear 
that the protocol also contains more specific agreements. 
  Which specific agreements? Ramiz Rizayev, Azerbaijani 
ambassador in Moscow and participant in the talks, stated in an 
interview with PRAVDA that the withdrawal of the Armenian troops 
from the occupied areas outside Nagorno-Karabakh has also been 
coordinated and that this is an indispensable condition of the 
truce. The approximate deadline -- 1 March -- was also 
determined, but the schedule and other details are still being 
discussed by the experts. The status of Nagorno-Karabakh and 
the fate of the enclave as a whole were not the subject of the 
talks and will be resolved later on during the peace process. 
  Despite the first optimistic results of the quadripartite 
meeting, so far it is difficult to judge whether serious 
progress has been reached in untying the tight Karabakh knot. 
There are no clear guarantees of how the commitments that have 
been assumed will be observed, and when and in what form 
peacekeeping forces will be put into operation. B. Yeltsin and 
N. Nazarbayev already tried to reconcile the opponents in 
Zheleznovodsk in fall 1991 (and, it seemed, not without 
success), and there have been several hopeful agreements within 
the framework of the CSCE. However, in the attempt to move from 
words to action, each time the peace signal turned out to be 
false. Will today's protocol stand the test of time? 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

