<H3> <TI>   Moscow Talks End in `Protocol for a Cease-Fire' </TI></H3>
<H4>   Russian Foreign Ministry Hails Protocol </H4>
<F P=102> LD2202223794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1817 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2202223794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Denis Perkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 22 TASS -- The Russian Foreign 
Ministry praised a special protocol signed by the Azerbaijani 
and Armenian defence ministers and a Nagorno-Karabakh military 
representative, a Foreign Ministry spokesman said on Tuesday [22 
February]. 
  The protocol was signed on February 18 as a result of talks 
mediated by Russian Defence Minister Pavel Grachev and attended 
by the Russian president's special envoy Vladimir Kazimirov. 
The document provides for a complete cease-fire and termination 
of combat operations, as well as for troops disengagement. At 
the moment. A joint group of experts is working out a procedure 
for putting this protocol into practice. 
  The Russian Foreign Ministry called upon all warring sides 
to 
strictly observe the reached agreements and to go ahead on their 
basis with concluding a full-scale political accord. 
  "The Russian Foreign Ministry welcomes the aspirations of 
the 
warring sides to put an end to bloodshed, to help fulfil 
resolutions by the U.N. Security Council to this effect and to 
promote an all-round settlement of the conflict within the 
framework of the CSCE peace conference on Nagorno-Karabakh," the 
ministry said in the statement. 

</TEXT>

