<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kravchuk Decides Not To Run for President </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302141294 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1130 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2302141294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] According to the message of the Ukrainian radio 
broadcast on Tuesday evening, in his interview with Radio 
Svoboda President Leonid Kravchuk declared about his intention 
not to participate in the presidential elections scheduled for 
June 26, 1994. 
  Explaining his move, he said that in his opinion it is 
hardly 
expedient to hold elections so soon. Kravchuk believes that 
presidential elections, to be held immediately after the 
parliamentary elections on March 27, will result in the 
excessive politicizing of society. 
  The second reason he gave for his unwillingness to run was 
the fact that he now bears a part of the responsibility for the 
present social and economic situation in Ukraine as "a man who 
is currently working." In his opinion, in the case of his 
participation, his contenders would spend their forces not to 
develop constructive programs but to prove that the present 
president has failed to fulfill his duties. 
  A commentator of the Ukrainian radio expressed regret due to 
the fact that this statement was provided for Radio Svoboda but 
not for the state TV and radio company. According to the 
commentator, "the presidential explanations do not look 
persuasive." "There are more questions than answers in the 
president's statement," said the commentator who preferred to 
stay anonymous. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

