<F P=100> CAUCASUS </F>
<F P=101> Armenia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Azerbaijani Military Options in Karabakh Said Exhausted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302104994 Moscow INTERFAX in English 0623 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2302104994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Presidential Bulletin" feature] </F>
  [Text] Baku's desire for regional truce follows a 
realization that ways of resolving the Armenian-Azeri conflict 
on the battlefield have been exhausted, a senior Armenian 
official told Interfax. 
  He also pointed to recent military successes by Karabakh 
forces which regained control of the Omar Pass in the Azeri 
region of Kelbajar and to the tough stand taken by Russian 
Defence Minister Pavel Grachev during recent talks between the 
Armenian and Azeri defence chiefs. The official said Baku must 
have realized that if Grachev wound up his mediation, "its only 
hope will be a military option which leads nowhere". 
  The Armenian official hopes the agreement will be 
implemented 
in stages. A permanent cease-fire must be followed by troop 
withdrawals, exchange of prisoners and negotiations on the 
status of Nagorno-Karabakh. He said the main thing now was to 
stop the bloodletting because negotiation was a lengthy process. 
  The source expressed regret that the international community 
should proceed from the principle of territorial integrity on 
resolving the conflict. He described it as a superb principle 
unless applied to the Karabakh issue. "This is the internal 
issue of Azerbaijan of which Karabakh used to be part until 
recently but it declared its independence following the 
national-liberation struggle", the source said. Therefore, the 
principle of integrity should not be applied to the disputed 
territory, he said. 
  In the meantime, head of the information and analysis center 
of Armenia's large opposition Dashnaktsutyun Party Bagrat 
Sadoian fears that any cease-fire will only play into the hands 
of Azerbaijan which ran out of its military resources after the 
failure of an offensive it began at the end of December. 
  Sadoian thinks Baku cannot put up with the idea of losing 
Karabakh and is now trying to regain it. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

