<F P=100> Azerbaijan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Karabakh Commander on Azeri `Blunder' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2202204694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1715 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2202204694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] In an interview with Interfax the Deputy Commander 
of Nagorno-Karabakh's defence forces, General Khristofor 
Ivanian, described the attempt to drive a wedge into Karabakh 
defences in Kelbajar District as "a gross blunder on the part of 
the Azeri command." 
  According to him, the Karabakh units holding most of the 
heights there did not find it hard 5 days ago to surround and 
neutralize a large Azeri army group. "The adventure in 
Kelbajar, which pursued largely political goals, turned for 
Azerbaijan into pointless losses; over 500 troops got frozen to 
death high in the mountains," Ivanian said. 
  In the meantime the Karabakh army's arsenal was supplemented 
with trophies: 12 armored vehicles, including five tanks, two 
152-mm self-propelled artillery installations, a jet rocket 
system, heavy guns and other military equipment. According to 
the general, about 20 Azeri servicemen surrendered. The 
Karabakh side lost 3 men; 15 troops were wounded. 
  The general believes that, having failed to score genuine 
success in its two-months-long offensive, Azerbaijan ought to 
get convinced once again that "to use the language of force 
toward the people of Karabakh" is useless. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

