<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Tajikistan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Afghanistan Accused of Interfering in Tajik Affairs </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2202154194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1501 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2202154194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Galina Gridneva] </F>
  [Text] Dushanbe February 22 TASS -- A note of the Tajik 
Foreign Ministry was sent to the Afghan consul in Dushanbe today 
to accuse the Afghan authorities of interference in Tajik 
internal affairs. The note to be passed over to the Afghan 
leaders says the Afghan side violates the bilateral treaty on 
friendship, cooperation and good-neighbourly relations signed in 
December 1993. 
  In the opinion of the Tajik side, the accusations are 
grounded with the assignment of Afghan border territories to 
militants of the Tajik opposition, who systematically shell 
Russian border posts and Tajik villages together with Afghan 
mujaheddin not controlled by the official Kabul authorities. 
  Several populated localities of the border Shuro-Abad region 
in the Tajik south were shelled on February 21 from Afghan 
territory, says the document. A many-hour fighting was imposed 
on the 12th border post of the Moscow border unit by a mixed 
group of Tajik militants and Afghan mujaheddin who infiltrated 
inside Tajikistan. 
  The Tajik government also has information on preparations 
for 
terrorist acts and acts of sabotage in the border Shaartuz, 
Kabodien, Pyandzh and some other regions in the Tajik south. 
  The Tajik side demands that the Afghan leadership take the 
most decisive measures to prevent hostile actions against 
sovereign Tajikistan and the Russian border units, says the 
document. Otherwise, the Tajik government preserves the right to 
stop armed provocations up to destruction of Tajik militants' 
bases on Afghan territory. 

</TEXT>

