<F P=100> Georgia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Gas Supplies From Turkmenistan To Continue </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2202180894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1432 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2202180894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Gas supplies to Georgia from Turkmenistan will 
continue in the coming days. An understanding was reached 
Monday during telephone talks between President Saparmurad 
Niyazov of Turkmenistan and the Georgian leader Eduard 
Shevardnadze, a spokesman for the Georgian leader has informed 
Interfax. 
  The spokesman said that Georgian Prime Minister Otar 
Patsatsiya is expected to visit Ashgabat this week to continue 
the talks on postponement of the Georgian gas-supply debt to 
Turkmenistan. 
  By different estimates the debt amounts to $100-400 Mn. 
  Meanwhile, the energy crisis in Georgia has reached a peak. 
For two days, the republic was only supplied with a minimal of 
electric energy owing to the accident at the Tbilisi 
hydro-electric station. Metro, TV and radio stations did not 
work in Tbilisi. There is no water supply in Tbilisi homes. 
Telephones are on the blink. 
  The leader of the Georgian Energy Department Yuriy Chediya 
has told Interfax that the Tbilisi hydro-electric station has 
been repaired and supplies energy once again. The spokesman 
said that the situation would be critical if gas supplies were 
cut. 

</TEXT>

