<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kebich, Birkavs Sign 8 Documents </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2102152594 Minsk BELAPAN in Belarusian 1309 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2102152594 </F>
<F P=104>  Minsk BELAPAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Belarusian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Latvian Prime Minister Valdis Birkavs paid a 
one-day visit to Belarus on 21 February. In the morning, he 
held talks with Belarusian Prime Minister Vyacheslav Kebich, as 
a result of which eight documents were signed. As BELAPAN 
learned, the documents concern, first of all, the state border 
between the two countries. The border is to remain the same as 
it was on 16 June 1940. During the talks, both sides agreed 
that it is necessary to expand cooperation between the two 
countries in various spheres of economy and politics. They 
particularly expressed their willingness to reach an agreement 
on mutually beneficial utilization of the Navapolatsk refinery 
and the Ventspils seaport. Also discussed was the possibility 
of establishing department stores in the capitals of both 
republics. Latvian products will be displayed, for example, by 
the Minsk supermarket Ryha. The situation of Belarusians in 
Latvia was also discussed at the meeting. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-37757 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov036_g_94003" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-036 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  23 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kebich Welcomes Cargo Transit Accord </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2102174594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1423 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2102174594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] At their meeting in Minsk on Monday the prime 
ministers of Belarus and Latvia signed a package of documents 
concerning the essential issues in their bilateral relations. 
  These include a treaty on legal aid, accords on ecological 
problems and on the transit of special cargoes through Latvia, 
and a trade agreement for 1994. In addition, Vyacheslav Kebich 
and Valdis Birkavs signed a document on forming commissions 
designed to demarcate the border between the two countries and 
ease the rules for its crossing for those who live in the border 
areas. 
  As Prime Minister Kebich said at the news conference given 
after the meeting, the document on the transit of special 
cargoes through Latvia "is very useful for Belarus," since it 
grants Minsk the opportunity to transport through Latvia its 
weapons exported to different countries. 
  According to Kebich, the document also makes it easier to 
resolve problems connected with oil imports from the United Arab 
Emirates and other countries in the Middle East. "Belarus will 
buy the oil which is cheaper," the prime minister stressed. In 
his view, Belarus should not get tied to the Friendship oil 
pipeline. 
  Prime Minister Birkavs told the news conference that ethnic 
Belarusians living in Latvia will be guaranteed all human 
rights, even though dual citizenship will not be introduced in 
his country. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

