<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Minsk Rally Demands Government Resignation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2202163794 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1500 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2202163794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] [Lyudmila Vilyuga] Today a continuation of the rally 
and strike started on 15 February at the initiative of the 
republican strike committee, the independent trade union and the 
Belarus People's Front, was expected in Independence Square in 
Minsk. The rally, which numbered about 1,500 people, however, 
did not turn into a large-scale event. It demanded that the 
government should resign, the parliament be dissolved and new 
elections to the Supreme Soviet be held. Incidentally, the last 
demand coincides with a demand put forward by the republican 
federation of trade unions. 
  Meanwhile, the people's deputies who met today after a break 
in the session were in no hurry to heed the voice of the people. 
They started with discussing the agenda. Today Stanislav 
Shushkevich, ex-chairman of the parliament, turned up in 
parliament for the first time since his resignation. Now he can 
appraise the Supreme Soviet's work under a different angle. 
  [Begin Shushkevich recording] The parliament does not want 
to 
heed the views of the minority. Its overwhelming majority is 
made up of old Communists elected when the Belarus Communist 
Party was in power. [end recording] 
  [Vilyuga] The parliamentary majority solved cadre issues 
quite efficiently today. Three generals took important offices: 
Uladimir Danko was appointed interior minister, Genadz Lavitski 
-- chairman of the KGB, and (Anatoliy Novikov) -- chairman of 
the Supreme Soviet's commission for national security and 
combating crime. Ivan Bambiza was elected new deputy chairman 
of the Supreme Soviet. 

</TEXT>

