<F P=100> BALTIC STATES </F>
<F P=101> Estonia </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia Begins To Demarcate Official Border </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2202212094 Tallinn BNS in English 1920 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> WS2202212094 </F>
<F P=104>  Tallinn BNS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Tallinn, Feb 22, BNS -- Russia announced today it 
will begin preparatory work to mark down the current borderline, 
what it declares the official border with Estonia. 
  Estonia, sticking to the border as established by the 1920 
Tartu peace treaty, has turned down any suggestions so far to 
give the current borderline a formal status. 
  The Russian Foreign Ministry and other departments involved 
in the work have started to draw up the respective documents, 
Sergei Prikhodko, head of the Bureau for the Baltics at the 2nd 
European department at the Foreign Ministry told reporters at a 
briefing in Moscow. 
  He said a situation when no clearly marked border exists in 
reality couldn't last forever. 
  The diplomat said Russia was forced to start marking the 
border unilaterally, as Estonia was not prepared to do it 
together. 
  He said a situation had emerged on the Estonian-Russian 
border that could lead to "severe consequences," adding that 
this was due to Estonia's attempts to "resurrect the 1920 Tartu 
Peace Treaty." 
  Expressing Russia's concern about frequent occasions of 
illegal border crossing and what he called "agitation carried 
out by Estonian emissaries" on the territories that were once 
part of Estonia, he said appeals to residents in those areas to 
take Estonian citizenship and get Estonian passports were "in 
violation of the Russian legislation." 
  At the same time Russia allows its citizens to have dual 
citizenship, a status that Estonian laws forbid. 
  Estonia in its official policy insists that the 1920 Tartu 
Peace Treaty remains in force and, thus, Estonia has the legal 
right for territories now formally part of Russia's Leningrad 
and Pskov regions, which went to Russia in the 1940's and 1950's. 
  Also the Estonian Constitution defines the country's borders 
as valid before the Soviet invasion of 1940. 
  Russia regards the peace treaty as having lost its validity. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-37770 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov036_t_94005" </HT>


