<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin Calls For Summit on Yugoslavia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302120294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1130 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2302120294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS corespondent Anna Melnikova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 23 TASS -- Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin called to hold a summit with leaders of four major NATO 
members to "put an end to the Yugoslav conflict". 
  The Russian president said on Wednesday [23 February] that 
he 
believes it possible to sign a joint agreement between leaders 
of Russia, the United States, Great Britain, France and Germany 
which would end the bloodshed in former Yugoslavia. 
  "Russia should more courageously and resolutely join the 
European and world community and other international 
organisations", Yeltsin told reporters after laying a wreath to 
the Tomb of the Unknown Soldier on Wednesday in connection with 
the Day of Motherland Defenders. 
  "Attempts of certain leaders to keep Russia away from 
solving 
international security issues is a discrimination. Russia has 
to and will participate in all major international events as a 
permanent member of the UN Security Council", the Russian 
president stressed. 
  He added that the NATO decision to bomb Bosnian Serbs 
"caused 
indignation not only among Russian diplomats, but among all 
citizens of Russia". 
  Russia had to resort to urgent measures which it had 
proposed 
to the United Nations a year ago. "The Russian leadership 
recommended to the United Nations to take Sarajevo under its 
administrative control as the most disputed city", Yeltsin said. 
  Russian contacts with Slobodan Milosevic and the trip of 
special envoy Vitaliy Churkin to Bosnia averted the catastrophe, 
according to the president. 
  "In contrast to NATO which announced an ultimatum to Serbs, 
Russia requested the Serbs to pull back their heavy guns", the 
president said adding that this was "a psycologically 
well-thought out move which has worked". 
  To ensure safety of the Serbs Russia sent 400 peace-keepers 
from Croatia to Sarajevo at a request of Milosevic. "Despite 
heavy snow the guys arrived in Sarajevo in time", Yeltsin said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

