<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Lavrov Reaffirms Position on NATO Ultimatum </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2002121794 Moscow Radio Rossii Network in Russian 1100 GMT 
20 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2002121794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Rossii Network </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Review of the Week" program] </F>
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] [Correspondent Vitaliy Buzuyev] 
Deputy Russian Foreign Minister Sergey Lavrov, in a telephone 
interview with our correspondent, said the following: 
  [Begin Lavrov recording] As far as an ultimatum is 
concerned, we have already set out our position, and President 
Yeltsin and the Russian foreign minister have stressed -- and so 
has the chairman of the government -- that an ultimatum is not 
the way we consider it is necessary to act in this situation. 
We have not recognized NATO's ultimatum, and we have stressed 
the need to work within the framework of the UN Security Council 
resolutions. These resolutions, as is known, state the need for 
all sides to take measures to lift the blockade of Sarajevo and 
they warn the sides that, in the event of the UN peacekeeping 
forces coming under attack, these forces will respond and will 
receive support. Only in these instances can the use of force 
be permitted, and we have explained this in detail in our 
statements. We have also counterposed attempts to, so to speak, 
solve matters by an ultimatum with a policy toward political 
work and vigorous diplomatic actions which have, generally 
speaking, brought results. Incidentally, we put forward the 
idea of lifting the blockade of Sarajevo quite some time ago -- 
if you want to be exact, we were speaking about it last year 
when we proposed more than once that the Security Council should 
be convened precisely to examine the question of lifting the 
blockade of Sarajevo, which is the key to a solution to the 
whole Bosnian problem. [end recording] 
  [Buzuyev] In the opinion of many observers, the Russian 
initiative restores our country's position as a player which 
should be reckoned with in the international arena. Whether we 
are too late will become clear in the next few days or even 
hours. 

</TEXT>

