<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Bonn Meeting on Bosnia Settlement Reported </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2202223394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 2049 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2202223394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Gennadiy Kulbitskiy] </F>
  [Text] Bonn February 22 TASS -- A working meeting of heads 
of diplomatic services of Russia, the United States and Canada, 
as well as the EC states and U.N. representatives expressed 
concern over situation in Bosnian regions and said that 
developments around Sarajevo caused by the NATO ultimatum and 
active efforts of the Russian leadership are a major step 
towards termination of war in Bosnia and Herzegovina. 
  The Russian Federation was represented by special envoy of 
the Russian president and Deputy Foreign Minister Vitaliy 
Churkin. 
  The negotiations decided to make use of the success achieved 
by joint efforts in settlement around Sarajevo and continue 
close interaction with the aim of immediate search for ways to 
settle the Bosnian conflict by all the warring sides, head of 
the German Foreign Ministry's political department Juergen 
Chrobog told a news conference here today. 
  The meeting praised possible achievement of understanding 
between the Bosnian Government and Bosnian Croats, said the 
German diplomat. 
  Possible uses of heavy armaments pulled back from Sarajevo 
in 
other Bosnian regions were described as a major problem. The 
meeting participants agreed to concentrate on the expansion of 
security zones, achieve stable truce in Sarajevo through 
efficient separation of the warring units, prevent the use of 
pulled back heavy armaments in other regions, ensure free access 
to the city of humanitarian convoys and restore normal life in 
Sarajevo with the help of U.N. units. 
  In the opinion of experts, it is necessary to replace U.N. 
personnel in Srebrenica and Jepa and ensure free access of 
humanitarian convoys to the area, immediately open the Tuzla 
airport for the delivery of humanitarian cargo, achieve truce 
and pullback of artillery and ensure access of humanitarian aid 
to Mostar, achieve efficient truce in central areas of Bosnia 
and ensure free access of humanitarian cargo in Maglaj. 
  Asked by ITAR-TASS whether the Bonn working meeting 
discussed 
a summit on Bosnian settlement, whose idea was considered during 
a telephone conversation of Russian President Boris Yeltsin and 
German Federal Chancellor Helmut Kohl late last week, the German 
Foreign Ministry's political department head said participants 
in the working meeting will inform the state heads of the 
meeting discussion and results. 
  The politicians will decide what kind of meeting should 
discuss Bosnian settlement. The issue was not discussed in 
detail, meeting participants need some time to think. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

