<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further Diplomatic Moves in Bosnia Planned </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2202152994 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1200 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2202152994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Presidential Aide D.B. Ryurikov by </F>
unidentified correspondent; place and date not given -- from the 
"Novosti" newscast] 
  [Text] Judging by U.S. President Clinton's statement, the 
United States is insisting on a wider use of diplomatic force to 
make good use of the precedent in Sarajevo. U.S. diplomats are 
already pressing for peace initiatives to be extended to other 
regions of Bosnia-Herzegovina. Today, the aide to the Russian 
president on external issues told our correspondent in some 
detail about Russia's stance on this question. 
  [Correspondent] Dmitriy Borisovich, how will Russia further 
develop its diplomatic initiative in this area? 
  [Ryurikov] Well, Russia has not stopped its initiatives, and 
it will continue to develop them very actively. They will 
concern the creation of a stable and peaceful situation in 
Sarajevo -- that is, lifting the blockade of this region and 
possibly placing it under UN administration -- and then reaching 
agreement on roughly the same actions in other security zones on 
Bosnian territory. Of course these must be peaceful, 
diplomatic, political solutions, and the process of seeking a 
political settlement of the problems of Bosnia as a whole must 
be sharply stepped up. This must be based on the EC plan, 
possibly with certain changes, trying to achieve a settlement as 
soon as possible in order to stop all hostilities. 

</TEXT>

