<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow Urges West To Make Muslims `Help Unblock' Sarajevo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2202205794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1937 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2202205794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Boris Sitnikov] </F>
  [Text] United Nations February 22 TASS -- Russia has urged 
the United States and the European Union "to exert the necessary 
influence" on Bosnian Muslims in order to avoid any possible 
provocations in Sarajevo. 
  "It is crucial in this critical moment to exclude a 
possibility of any provocations and sabotage of the peace 
process. Not only Sarajevo's fate but the fate of Bosnian 
peaceful settlement on the whole depends on this", the Russian 
Foreign Ministry said in a statement distributed in the United 
Nations on Tuesday [22 February]. 
  Russia called on the West "to exert the necessary pressure 
on 
the Bosnian Government to make it cooperate with the United 
Nations in unblocking and demilitarizing Sarajevo", according to 
the statement circulated as a U.N. Security Council document. 
  If the U.S.A. and the European Union member countries press 
on Bosnian Muslims to make them help unblock Sarajevo, the West 
would act "on the same lines it declared while saying that 
political settlement of the conflict would be preferable", the 
document says. 
  It recalled the Russian initiative which made Bosnian Serbs 
pull back heavy guns from Sarajevo and added that Russia's 
"consequent line which excludes any unilateral ultimatums has 
yielded results". 
  "We are accounting that goodwill which was shown by one of 
the conflicting sides in the moment critical to the (conflict's) 
settlement will evoke equally concrete responsive moves", it 
reads. 
  Russia also proposed that after unblocking Sarajevo, the 
United Nations urgently consider ways of establishing its 
administration in the city and measures to stregthen other safe 
areas on the Bosnian territory. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

