<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Holds News Conference With Jeszenszky </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2202123794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1203 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2202123794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS special correspondents Sergey Zhirnikhin and </F>
Georgiy Shmelev] 
  [Text] Budapest February 22 TASS -- "Our talks with Andrey 
Kozyrev focused on problems of bilateral relations between 
Moscow and Budapest," Hungarian Foreign Minister Geza Jeszenszky 
told a joint press conference here on Monday evening [21 
February]. 
  According to the Hungarian minister, Russia is today the 
second largest economic and trade partner of Hungary, while the 
latter holds eighth place in the list of Russia's major economic 
partners. "Very important for the development of our cultural 
cooperation are contacts between the religious leaders of the 
two countries," the Hungarian minister said. He recalled in 
this connection that Budapest would be visited on March 3 by 
Patriarch of Moscow and All of Russia Aleksius II. 
  Dwelling on the Hungarian foreign policy's orientation, 
Jeszenszky noted that integration into the European structures 
of the North Atlantic treaty Organisation and the European Union 
were of primary importance for Budapest, as well as the 
country's active participation in the CSCE process and in the 
implementation of the "Partnership for Peace" programme. 
Touching on the situation in Bosnia, the Hungarian foreign 
minister stressed that "the stands of Budapest and Moscow on 
this question have no serious distinctions". 
  "Russia attaches great importance to relations with 
Hungary," 
Foreign Minister Andrey Kozyrev told the press conference. 
"This is specially noted in the treaty between the two 
countries, recently signed at summit level." The minister 
expressed the hope that it would be ratified by the new Russian 
parliament. 
  "I wish to back my friend Jeszenszky's words about the 
prospects for relations between Russia and Hungary," Kozyrev 
stated. "Russia has no hegemonic or neo-imperialist designs in 
Central and Eastern Europe. The attraction of the peoples of 
our countries towards each other is perfectly natural," he added. 

</TEXT>

