<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Goes to Poland </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302073094 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 2340 
GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2302073094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS special correspondents Aleksandr Potemkin and </F>
Georgiy Shmelev] 
  [Text] Krakow, 23 Feb -- If all Russo-Polish talks go as 
well as the present talks, the path to friendship and 
cooperation will be covered much faster. That was how Andrey 
Kozyrev and Andrzej Olechowski, the foreign ministers of Russia 
and Poland, summed up the progress and results of the bilateral 
talks that ended here late in the evening on 22 February. 
  During the meeting, the whole spectrum of relations between 
the two states was examined, said A. Kozyrev, replying to 
questions from ITAR-TASS correspondents. A number of very 
interesting initiatives were put forward, covering the economy, 
culture and social relations between our countries. 
  Unfortunately, the Russian minister noted, many specific 
accords reached during Russian President Boris Yeltsin's visit 
to Warsaw last August have not been fully implemented. That is 
why the present talks are extremely important. We have met in 
order to "puff along," as Mr. Olechowski says, that is, to urge 
these processes on. We are on the right path, A. Kozyrev 
pointed out when appraising the state of bilateral relations. 
In the Russian minister's opinion, the part to be played by 
Poland and other Central European countries in building a united 
Europe is very important. Equitable Russo-Polish cooperation 
should be a substantial factor in it. 
  Our states official relations "do not look at all bad," A. 
Olechowski observed. The task now is to fill them "with 
benevolent content." Mr. Kozyrev and I have discussed a number 
of concrete actions and have made a number of concrete 
decisions: "We are thinking about some, we are working on 
others, and we have agreed on a third group." All that is the 
"puffing along," as my counterpart put it jokingly, the 
development of our relations . 
  Commenting at the request of the ITAR-TASS correspondent on 
the thoughts of the Polish mass media on the present role of 
Russia -- as "adversary or partner of Poland," A. Olechowski 
said: "Neighbors should never be adversaries. The question now 
is how to pave the way as quickly as possible from relations of 
neighbors to relations of very good neighbors, and then to 
relations of a friend." It is understandable that it is 
impossible to achieve this in a few days, but we should try to 
achieve it as quickly as possible, the Polish minister pointed 
out. 
  Speaking about Russia's attitude to the problem of Poland 
joining NATO, A. Kozyrev noted that this question had been 
discussed "in a very confidential and realistic way." It is now 
necessary to concentrate on participation in the "Partnership 
for Peace" program, the minister said. There was no ruling out 
one country or another joining NATO. And these countries should 
find their own way to making a decision. It is possible, he 
pointed out, that Russia may join NATO too. But there may also 
be other options. A machinery of interaction of the partners 
has already been created now. This is the North Atlantic 
Cooperation Council, A. Kozyrev pointed out. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

