<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Ukrainian Prime Minister Talks With Chernomyrdin </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD1802204494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1909 GMT 18 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD1802204494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Acting Prime Minister of Ukraine Yuhym Zvyahilskyy 
who arrived on an informal flying visit to Moscow has held one 
hour of private talks with his Russian counterpart Viktor 
Chernomyrdin, Russian diplomats in Moscow told INTERFAX. Soon 
after the talks, the Ukrainian official flew out to Kiev to 
continue work as usual. 
  No word was given of the details of the meeting. However, a 
senior Russian diplomat linked Zvyahilskyy's surprise visit to a 
recent stay in Moscow by pro-Moscow Crimean President Yuriy 
Meshkov. Meshkov had held negotiations with top government and 
parliamentary officials in the Russian capital inviting leading 
economist Yevgeniy Saburov to head the Crimean cabinet of 
ministers. 
  The two sides may have also discussed the Rbl[Rubles] 1 
Tn[trillion] debt Kiev has run for gas imports from Russia by 
the end of January, the diplomat said. Although Russia's chief 
gas exporter, Gazprom, threatened to cut off gas supply to 
Ukraine, it has so far suspended the measure. The diplomat 
believes the two prime ministers may have reached agreement by 
telephone on how to settle the debt and discussed the details on 
Friday. 

</TEXT>

