<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin, Akayev Discuss Wide Range of Issues </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2202132494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1215 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2202132494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russian President Boris Yeltsin and President of 
Kyrgyzstan Askar Akayev met in Kremlin on Tuesday morning [22 
February]. 
  Boris Yeltsin's press service announced that the two 
presidents had discussed a wide range of issues pertaining to 
bilateral trade and economic cooperation and the status of 
ethnic Russians in Kyrgyzstan. 
  The two officials also exchanged views on the situation in 
the CIS and on ways of strengthening it; the situation in 
Central Asia and joint efforts to settle the Tajik conflict, and 
on other international problems. 
  Akayev said that he had brought in a package of proposals on 
solving the problem of ethnic Russian's migration from 
Kyrgyzstan. Following their discussion with the Russian 
president, Akayev will present them to the CIS summit to be held 
in March. "I think we must share our ideas with all of the CIS 
leaders because this is a problem of common concern," he said. 
  He told Yeltsin that the situation in his republic was 
stable 
and quiet. 

</TEXT>

