<F P=102>  LD2202175794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1624 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2202175794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Dmitriy Chubarov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 22 TASS -- Legalization of ethnic 
discrimination in Latvia "becomes a prime concern of the Russian 
president, the government and the public," says a letter of 
Russian President Boris Yeltsin to Latvian leader Guntis Ulmanis. 
  The letter was passed over on Monday [21 February] by the 
Russian ambassador to Riga, sources at the Russian Foreign 
Ministry's press and information department told ITAR-TASS here 
today. 
  The Russian president stressed the priority of settlement of 
the citizenship problem in Latvia with a bilateral agreement. 
In his words, integration of ethnic Russians with public life 
of the independent Latvian Republic would open up a new chapter 
in relations with Latvia, "with which Russia is connected with 
thousands of ties and wants to have good-neighbourly relations 
and mutually beneficial relationship". 
  According to the letter, the Russian and Latvian delegations 
are working to achieve progress in the elaboration of a treaty 
on Russian troops withdrawal, agreements on social protection of 
Russian servicemen, military pensioners and members of their 
families, as well as on the Russian radar station in Skrunda. 
  The signing of these documents would boost settlement of 
other complicated issues of bilateral relations, stressed the 
president's letter. 

</TEXT>

