<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Commentary on DPRK Nuclear Issue, Third Round Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  SK1802123994 Moscow Radio Moscow in Korean 1200 GMT 15 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> SK1802123994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Radio Moscow </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Korean </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Commentary by Korolev: "The Prospect of International </F>
Inspections on DPRK Nuclear Facilities" from the "Today's World" 
program] 
  [Text] The final date -- 21 February -- when the DPRK has 
to give a clear answer on allowing an international inspection 
team to enter its nuclear facilities is approaching. 
  The problem lies in Washington's strict demand and the 
International Atomic Energy Agency [IAEA] asking Pyongyang to 
open the two facilities suspected of secretly developing nuclear 
weapons. 
  The future of the third round of U.S.-DPRK talks depends on 
the DPRK leaders' attitude toward this problem. Issues related 
to normalizing the two countries relations should be discussed 
in the talks. 
  Considering all the facts, it is of most concern that 
Pyongyang positively resolve the issue for economic reasons. 
Judging from the result of the past two rounds of talks, the 
DPRK seems to be well prepared for IAEA inspections of all 
nuclear facilities. 
  In the talks with the IAEA held in Vienna concerning the 
dispute of the details of inspections, it was agreed that two 
important facilities in the DPRK territory would not be taken 
into account [kaman haji anta]. 
  According to data in possession [kajigo innun charyo], 
weapon 
[word indistinct] needed for nuclear warheads could be produced 
at these facilities. It is worrisome [pulan hada] how Pyongyang 
will answer Washington and the IAEA. 
  It is clear that the situation in the region would be 
aggravated if DPRK does not change its attitude on the nuclear 
issue. This is because Washington, Tokyo, and some other 
countries insist that a series of sanctions be imposed on the 
DPRK. They could also bomb [pokkyok halsudo itta] the nuclear 
facilities in the DPRK. 
  On the other hand, other countries oppose such hard-line 
measures. Russia insists on the early resolution of the nuclear 
weapons issue on the Korean peninsula, constructive dialogue 
between parties concerned, and effective cooperation between the 
DPRK and the IAEA. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

