<H3> <TI>   Prospects for Treaty Discussed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2202110694 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1017 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2202110694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondents Anatoliy Krasnov and </F>
Dmitriy Chubarov] 
  [Text] Moscow February 22 TASS -- A mixed Russo-Japanese 
group met today to discuss prospects for signing a peace treaty 
between the two countries. 
  "We are satisfied with the dialogue," the leader of the 
Russian delegation to the talks, Deputy Foreign Minister 
Aleksandr Panov told the press on Tuesday morning the 
consultations have confirmed Japan's support for Russian 
reforms. The process is already underway of turning the Group 
of Seven into a group of eight by admitting Russia to the club 
of the world's strongest powers. Japan has also showed a full 
understanding of the need to help the United Nations in solving 
international problems, Panov said. 
  As concerns the peace treaty between Russia and Japan, the 
Russian deputy minister said it was necessary to "set the scene" 
for a favourable dialogue on this subject. To facilitate the 
creation of a favourable atmosphere, the two delegations decided 
not to emphasize the territorial issue at their Tuesday meeting. 
  Panov said a decision is due to be reached on Tuesday on the 
date of the Japanese Foreign Minister Tsutomu Hata's visit to 
Moscow. 

