<H3> <TI>   Navy Sees No Threat from U.S.-Japanese Exercises </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2102140794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1348 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2102140794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anatoliy Yurkin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 21 TASS -- Scenarios of an armed 
attack on the Russian Far East which were simulated at joint 
U.S.-Japanese command and staff exercises, do not threaten the 
security and national interests of the Russian Federation, 
although they are a relapse of the Cold War, said on Monday 
representatives of the Russian chief naval staff. 
  They commented on an article in Sunday's Japanese newspaper 
MAINICHI that the United States and Japan conducted exercises 
codenamed C-1, C-2 and C-3, during which representatives of the 
Pentagon and the Japanese Defence Agency annually drafted plans 
for invading the Russian Maritime Territory, the South Kurils 
and Sakhalin. 
  In the opinion of Russian experts, the article does not 
reflect present-day realities. The world has changed, as has 
the nature of relations between countries. For instance, Russia 
and the United States will stage a joint exercise with beaching 
a landing party. 
  Russian-Japanese contacts have also become more active. They 
became more open and trustworthy. 
  Russia has adequate forces to protect its Far East both from 
land and sea, representatives of the Russian chief naval staff 
claimed. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

