<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Moscow `Not Quite Satisfied' With Turks' Rules on Straits </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2202185494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1505 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2202185494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Diplomatic Panorama" feature: Reports by </F>
diplomatic correspondents Dmitriy Voskoboinikov, Igor Porshnev, 
Vitaliy Trubetskoy and others] 
  [Text] "Russia is not quite satisfied" with the rules for 
the passage of ships through the Black Sea straits, Bosporus and 
Dardanelles, established by Turkey early this year. A Russian 
delegation led by the First Deputy Director of the Foreign 
Ministry's legal department, Yakov Ostrovskiy, left for Ankara 
on Monday to discuss this problem. Interfax learned this from a 
high-ranking Russian diplomat in charge of relations with Turkey. 
  The passage of ships through the Black Sea straits is 
regulated by the Montreux Convention signed in 1938 by the USSR, 
Turkey and some other countries, he explained. "Provisions of 
that convention satisfy Russia. As for Ankara, while 
proclaiming its adherence to the convention verbally, in fact it 
interprets the document rather freely," the diplomat said. 
  The new Turkish rules, he explained, stipulate that the 
ships 
passing through the straits must necessarily be accompanied by 
pilots (Interfax's note: under the convention pilots can be 
used only with the captains' consent). 
  Moreover, Interfax's interviewee noted, Turkey's provision 
that large ships must pass through Bosporus strictly in their 
turn "is not quite in line" with the convention. "Under the new 
Turkish rules, when a large ship enters the strait, the 
remaining ones must wait. This creates numerous 
inconveniences," the Russian diplomat said. 
  Turkey established "a very complicated procedure" for the 
passage of nuclear-armed ships, he pointed out. Preliminary 
notifications and the observance of some other formalities are 
required for the passage of such ships. "This is understandable. 
Istanbul is a city populated by 12 million people, and any 
accident may result in great casualties. Nevertheless we 
believe, and our view is shared by many Turks, that such issues 
should be resolved in the framework of an international 
conference. Such a conference may be convened in the near 
future," the diplomat concluded. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

