<F P=100> UKRAINE </F>
<F P=101> International Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russia Continues To Supply Gas to Country </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2202235794 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1950 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2202235794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The head of the press office of the Ukrainian State 
Committee for Oil and Gas, Stepan Yalovega, has confirmed that 
Turkmenistan cut off deliveries of its natural gas to Ukraine. 
At the same time, he told Interfax-Ukraine that Russia 
continued to supply Ukraine with gas. 
  According to Yalovega, Ukrainian consumers "have nothing 
special to worry about, for the republic's facilities store gas 
in sufficient quantities which would last until the end of the 
heating season." 
  Ukrainian Vice Prime Minister Valentin Landyk told a press 
conference in Kiev today that Ukraine will send 60,000 tons of 
grain to Turkmenistan to reimburse part of its debt for Turkmen 
gas that he estimated at $150 Mn. However, Turkmenistan 
believes that the debt has already reached $700 Mn. 
  Landyk added that a telephone conversation between acting 
Ukrainian Prime Minister Yefim Zvyagilskiy and the Turkmen 
leadership failed to help resume the deliveries. 
  In 1993, Ukraine received 25.5 Bn cubic meters of gas from 
Turkmenistan and another 69 Bn cubic meters from Russia. 

</TEXT>

