<H3> <TI>   Latvian Prime Minister Arrives in Minsk for Talks </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2102130094 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1111 GMT 21 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2102130094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Latvian Prime Minister Valdis Birkavs arrived in 
Minsk on Monday morning. On the same day he started talks with 
Belarusian Prime Minister Vyacheslav Kebich at the government 
residence. 
  A bilateral agreement on creating a commission for the 
demilitarization and demarcation of the Belarusian-Latvian 
border and on a simplified procedure for border crossing by 
inhabitants of border areas is expected to be signed in Minsk. 
  Birkavs and Kebich are expected to sign a treaty on legal 
assistance between Latvia and Belarus, a bilateral agreement on 
ecological problems, and a trade/economic agreement for 1994. 
  A spokesman for the Latvian Government told Interfax, 
Birkavs 
is accompanied by a government delegation including railway and 
economics ministers, the commander of the border guard brigade 
and other officials. 

</TEXT>

