<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Further on Amnesty Provisions </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK2302085094 Moscow SEGODNYA in Russian 23 Feb 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> MK2302085094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow SEGODNYA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report: "New Triumph of a `Package Method'"] </F>
  [Text] According to "Yabloko" deputy Vyacheslav 
Shostakovskiy, following a protracted discussion yesterday the 
State Duma Council decided to merge into one package two issues 
that have lately caused the deepest divisions between factions: 
on a wide-ranging amnesty and on setting up a commission to 
investigate the events of September-October 1993 in Moscow. 
Leaders of conservative factions, who have up to now demanded 
that the commission be vested with the broadest powers possible, 
agreed to persuade their deputies to refrain altogether from 
intervening in the investigation conducted by the prosecutor's 
office, and to act as if the vote on setting up a commission 
never took place. Their political rivals agreed in response to 
add a number of "political" provisions to the amnesty decree. 
The decision on the "purely criminal" amnesty, however, will 
still be made separately from decisions on the "political and 
economic" amnesty. Another participant in the meeting, however, 
told SEGODNYA that "A political amnesty does not mean at all 
that all those charged with organizing rebellions in 1991 and 
1993 and the instigators of last May's disturbances will be 
pardoned at once." 

</TEXT>

