<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   CIA Employee Arrested for Spying for Russia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302090594 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 0751 
GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2302090594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Andrey Palariya] </F>
  [Text] Moscow, 23 Feb -- The U.S. Government has brought 
charges against CIA employee Aldrich Ames and his wife Maria 
Ames, accusing them of spying for the former Soviet Union and 
then Russia. The U.S. Justice Department said that Ames and his 
wife were arrested on Monday during a joint operation conducted 
by the CIA and the FBI. According to the information of the 
Justice Department, the Ames had been spying against the United 
States since 1985 and had received more than $1.5 million for 
that, which they deposited in bank accounts in the United States 
and abroad. 
  Yuriy Kobaladze, head of the Russian Foreign Intelligence 
Service press office, whom an ITAR-TASS correspondent contacted 
by telephone this morning, declined to comment on the case of 
the arrest of the U.S. couple accused of spying for Russia. 
However, he remarked that "this question should be put, rather, 
to the CIA." 
  At the same time it seems that there's no point in blowing 
up 
a political scandal out of this episode. After all, even in a 
changing world, intelligence remains intelligence with the 
specific means and interests that are peculiar to it. 
Incidentally, the leadership of the United States and other 
Western countries have confirmed on several occasions that they 
have no intention of curtailing intelligence activity against 
Russia. 

</TEXT>

