<F P=100> INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Georgia, Abkhazia Resume Peace Talks in Geneva 22 Feb </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  AU2202140694 Paris AFP in English 1342 GMT 22 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> AU2202140694 </F>
<F P=104>  Paris AFP </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Geneva, Feb 22 (AFP) -- Georgia and the breakaway 
western region of Abkhazia resumed peace talks here on Tuesday 
under UN auspices with Russian participation, in a third round 
of negotiations which started last October. 
  UN spokeswoman Therese Gastaut said the aim of the two to 
three day session was to achieve an overall settlement. Topping 
the agenda are the return of 200,000 to 300,000 refugees who 
fled Abkhazia in last year's fighting, and a discussion of 
Abkhazia's political status. 
  Under the old Soviet constitution, Abkhazia was an 
autonomous 
republic within Georgia. The speaker of its parliament in 
Sukhumi, Vladislav Ardzinba, told the press here that Abkhazia 
could choose between independence or coexistence in equality 
with Georgia. Georgian leader Eduard Shevardnadze has insisted a 
solution must respect Georgia's territorial integrity. 
  The previous round of talks ended in mid-January with 
agreement in principle on the withdrawal of troops and a 
demilitarisation zone between the belligerents. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

