<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kozyrev Says Ames Case Must Not Be `Politicized' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402135094 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1333 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402135094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS diplomatic correspondent Georgiy Shmelev] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 24 TASS -- Russian foreign minister 
said the Ames' affair should not be politicized and forefronted 
in Russian-American relations. The problem should be handled by 
people responsible for this specific sphere, who will look into 
particulars, collect comprehensive information and make 
appropriate decisions. 
  The Russian minister was referring to the case of the former 
CIA counter-intelligence department leader Aldrich H. Ames and 
his wife whom the U.S. Administration accused of spying for the 
former Soviet Union and Russia. 
  According to the Russian minister, Russian-American 
relations 
have reached a very high level of partnership and cooperation 
for "cases like this one" to overshadow them. 
  Responding to a question from ITAR-TASS, Andrey Kozyrev 
admitted that "espionage stories" do crop up, regrettably, in 
relations between different countries from time to time, even if 
they are NATO allies, or between the United States and Israel. 
  Andrey Kozyrev expressed the hope that the "Ames problem" is 
in no way linked to the Russian president's latest initiative 
concerning Bosnia. It would be better, he said, not to 
politicize or ideologize the situation but let relevant services 
of the two countries handle it. 
  What is most important is for us "to continue cooperation 
and 
not to attach undue, hypertrophied significance to this case", 
Kozyrev said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

