<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Promises To Boost `Peaceful Offensive' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302190394 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1831 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2302190394 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 23 (TASS) -- Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin said on Wednesday [23 February] that the Sarajevo crisis 
was a test for the Russian foreign policy and promised to boost 
"peaceful offensive" to achieve a breakthrough in the general 
Bosnian settlement. 
  "The Bosnian crisis was a test of the firmness of our course 
in the world which showed the true potential of the Russian 
foreign policy", Yeltsin said at a meeting with Moscow teenagers 
studying in military colleges. 
  "In close cooperation with the United Nations and our 
partners we shall boost the peaceful offensive. The objective 
is that the ceasefire in sarajevo becomes a breakthrough to 
peace in the whole of Bosnia", the president stressed. 
  The crisis tested "our capability to resolutely defend the 
national and state interests of the country. Russia, as a UN 
Security Council member, as an equal participant of the 
community of democratic states demonstrated its right to 
participate in adopting key decisions of the world politics... 
which concern its lawful interests and international 
obligations. Our voice was heard in the world", the president 
said. 
  "The mechanism of partnership with the West was also tested. 
Although not immediately, with faults, but it did work", the 
president said adding that Russian stance on dialogue and 
cooperation with leading powers of the world has justified 
itself. 
  "The Sarajevo crisis has also spotlit the correctness of our 
course towards all-round strengthening of the United Nations as 
the major international organisation in ensuring peace", Yeltsin 
stressed. 
  As a result a ceasefire in Sarajevo was achieved without a 
further escalation of the military conflict, according to the 
president. "The logics of peace must, finally, win over 
nationalistic emotions which brought the peoples of 
Bosnia-Herzegovina to the top limit of human sufferings", 
Yeltsin said. 
  The president expressed hope that the conflciting sides 
would 
stand up to their commitments, ensure a reliable ceasefire and 
avert provocations against international peace-keepers, 
including the Russian force in Sarajevo. 

</TEXT>

