<H3> <TI>   Kostikov Says Yeltsin Won in Bosnia Where Others Failed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302173194 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1500 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2302173194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [From the "Novosti" newscast] </F>
  [Text] [Announcer] President Yeltsin condemned attempts by 
some Western leaders to stop Russia from resolving some 
important world issues. Here is the opinion of Boris Yeltsin's 
press secretary, Vyacheslav Kostikov, on the latest events 
around Yugoslavia. 
  [Begin Kostikov recording] I would like to recall in this 
respect that recently the opposition accused the president of 
all the deadly sins: in betraying Russia's interests and in 
selling himself to the West, and in playing to the foreign 
policy tune of the United States... How much speculation there 
were around trips to Yugoslavia. All and sundry went there, in 
an attempt to earn some political brownie points on the Yugoslav 
crisis. 
  President Yeltsin, however, managed to succeed where our 
political chatterboxes failed -- he demonstrated in deed the 
clause, enshrined in the new constitution, that it is the 
President of Russia who is the guarantor of Russia's national 
security. 
  A few more words on the president's role in these events. 
Let us word this issue in simple terms: Who, except for 
President Yeltsin, could say today such a weighty and decisive 
word -- so that it would have been heard in Sarajevo, Bonn, and 
Washington -- in the whole world, as a fact. There is no other 
person like this now. [end recording] 

</TEXT>

