<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Military Official on Redeployment of Troops in Sarajevo </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302205694 Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network in Russian 1800 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2302205694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow Ostankino Television First Channel 
Network </F>



<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Interview with Colonel General Yevgeniy Podkolzin, </F>
commander of Russia's Airborne troops, by Vladimir Solovyev, in 
Eastern Slavonia on 23 February -- live or recorded] 
  [Text] [Solovyev] Today on the Day of Defenders of the 
Fatherland at the main base of the Russian battalion in the 
former Yugoslavia in Eastern Slavonia, the traditional parade 
with presentation of medals was not held. Parades have been 
postponed until better times. Out of 1,200 soldiers and 
officers, 400 have been dispatched to Sarajevo from here. 
  [Podkolzin] Today they have already been fully deployed 
there, they have been deployed normally. There is electricity. 
So far there is no heating, but it was promised that in the 
course of the next two days they would be supplied with heating. 
  The battalion has already received a combat task. Today the 
battalion is serving in the main areas: it is guarding one area 
for the collection of the Serb weapons under an accord which was 
reached between the Muslims and the Serbs -- and one group is 
today serving at Sarajevo airport. Well, and the others have 
received the task of patrolling the separation line between the 
Serbs and the Muslims. I got in touch with General Rose, and he 
said that on the whole they would be serving in very difficult 
sectors, difficult areas. We were on the brink of this disaster 
but both the Serbs and Muslims have carried out their 
obligations as a result of which the strike was called off, and 
let's pray that there won't be another one. 
  [Solovyev] Do you think that your battalion will be there 
for 
a long time? 
  [Podkolzin] Until they set about the next stage of the 
cease- 
fire -- this is the opening of the roads for the delivery of 
humanitarian aid and other issues -- no less than two months 
will elapse -- but as a whole, it would appear that the 
contingent will have to be kept there probably no less than two 
years; this is my personal opinion. 

</TEXT>

