<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Criticizes NATO Moves in Bosnia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302184594 Belgrade TANJUG in English 1805 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2302184594 </F>
<F P=104>  Belgrade TANJUG </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Warsaw, Feb 23 (TANJUG) -- Russian Foreign Minister 
Andrey Kozyrev on Wednesday [23 February] sharply criticized 
NATO members for trying to solve the Bosnian conflict on their 
own, and called for joint actions to achieve peace in Bosnia. 
  Russia was ready to send more troops to Bosnia, if it was 
necessary, Kozyrev said in an interview to the Polish television 
in Krakow, where he took part in the [word indistinct] Russian 
confermce on the new partnership. 
  It was a big delusion to think that NATO was able to solve 
every problem unilaterally. He criticized NATO members for 
deciding about the Sarajevo action without prior consultation 
with the east. 
  NATO was last week ready to launch air strikes in the 
Sarajevo area acting on the ultimatum to the warring sides to 
demilitarize that city. In reality, the threats were addressed 
to the Bosnian Serbs alone. 
  The Bosnian Serbs started withdrawing heavy weapons around 
Sarajevo on Friday, only after the Moscow initiative and 
guarantees, and Russian peacekeepers were deployed on the line 
dividing the Serb and Moslem side. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

