<F P=100> CENTRAL ASIA </F>
<F P=101> Kazakhstan </F>
<H3> <TI>   Talks Held on Greater Involvement in CSCE </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302100794 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0901 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2302100794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By KAZTAG correspondent Ivan Zakharchenko for TASS] </F>
  [Text] Almaty February 23 TASS -- Kazakhstan is striving to 
get involved heavier in the Conference on Security and 
Cooperation in Europe (CSCE). This will be promoted by the 
opening of Kazakhstan's diplomatic missions in more European 
countries. 
  This was mentioned during a meeting on Tuesday between 
Kazakhstan Vice-President Eric Asanbayev [name and title as 
received] and CSCE Secretary-General Wilhelm Hoeynck who arrived 
in Almaty for a working visit. The sides agreed that more 
effort should be exerted to put a stop to conflicts in Central 
Asia, specifically in Tajikistan. 
  On the same day Wilhelm Hoeynck met with Kazakh Foreign 
Minister Tuleutay Suleymenov. It was noted during the 
conversation that following a meeting in Rome of foreign 
ministers of CSCE participating countries, new sovereign states 
in Central Asia, also Kazakhstan, strengthen their relations 
with that international organisation and are involved in joint 
work with CSCE. 
  In the Friendship House in the evening, Wilhelm Hoeynck met 
with representatives of non-governmental and public 
organisations and the media and answered their questions. 
  The CSCE secretary-general leaves for Bishkek on Wednesday. 

</TEXT>

