<F P=100> WESTERN REGION </F>
<F P=101> Belarus </F>
<H3> <TI>   Border With Russia Deemed To Be `Quite Different' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  WS2302173794 Minsk VO SLAVU RODINY in Russian 19 Feb 94 p 1 </F>
<F P=103> WS2302173794 </F>
<F P=104>  Minsk VO SLAVU RODINY </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Report by V. Kuts: "From Mutual Rights to Mutual </F>
Obligations"] 
  [Text] A draft agreement on border issues, which was 
discussed by the heads of Russian and Belarusian border 
departments [as published] in Minsk in mid-February, can become 
a basic document for further regulations of relations between 
both countries, including the issues concerning the external CIS 
borders. 
  If the internal CIS borders are to block a free transfer of 
goods and services, then the economic union proclaimed by CIS 
state heads will be devoid of all sense. With regard to this, 
the need for safe protection of the CIS external borders 
emerges, thus providing relations between both countries with a 
greater mutual responsibility. Now, while protecting the 
borders with the non-CIS countries, Belarus will protect not 
only its national interests, but also Russian ones. The Russian 
Federation will commit itself to analogous obligations. The 
question regards a quite different type of relations between the 
two states. These relations, as is assumed, will evolve from a 
system of mutual rights to a system of mutual obligations, which 
will help to save significant material means. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

