<F P=100> National Affairs </F>
<H3> <TI>   Parliament Ratifies Consular Convention With Russia </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302225194 Kiev UNIAN in Ukrainian 1650 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2302225194 </F>
<F P=104>  Kiev UNIAN </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Ukrainian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Kiev--The Supreme Council of Ukraine recently 
ratified the Consular Convention between Ukraine and the Russian 
Federation that was signed on 15 January 1993 during President 
of Ukraine Leonid Kravchuk's visit to Moscow, said Natalya 
Zarudna, the head of department of the Information Directorate 
at Ukraine's Foreign Affairs Ministry, at a briefing on 22 
February. The Russian Federal Assembly has not ratified the 
document yet. 
  The consular convention is based on the principles of the 
Vienna Convention on Consular Relations of 24 April 1963. It is 
a bilateral agreement that supplements the principles of this 
multilateral international legal act. The convention determines 
the procedure for the establishment of consular offices and 
appointment of consular officials; consular functions, benefits 
for consular officials and their rights and duties as to the 
protection of their citizens' interests. 
  According to Natalya Zarudna, the ratification of the 
convention will promote the establishment and development of 
Ukrainian-Russian consular relations, as well as the protection 
of rights and interests of Ukrainian and Russian citizens. 
Ukraine has already signed such conventions with China, 
Romania, Hungary, Poland, and Kazakhstan. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

