<H3> <TI>   Kazannik Welcomes Remarks on Crime </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402140994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1352 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402140994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow February 24 -- Russian Prosecutor-General 
Aleksey Kazannik expressed his approval of President Yeltsin's 
emphasis on the strengthening of the Russian state, law and 
order, and the fight against crime, as expressed in the 
president's first annual address to the Federal Assembly. 
  In an interview with ITAR-TASS, Kazannik noted that, "Boris 
Yeltsin perfectly correctly laid out a plan of legislative work. 
Without that it will be impossible to ensure law and order". 
  The procurator-general said he was sure that, after the 
adoption of the anti-crime programme which the Russian president 
is now intensively working on, law and order bodies will find it 
much easier to increase the strength of laws in the Russian 
society. 
  The president's address emphasized that, "A law-based state 
should be a strong one in order to guarantee peoples' safety, 
strike out against crime, and begin an offensive against 
corruption. A strong state is the basis for the continuation of 
reforms, the overcoming of the country's crisis, the 
establishment of basic economic restructuring, and the creation 
of conditions for economic stabilisation and growth". 
  It was also noted in the address that, "In a law-based 
state, 
power is limited by the law, which is a necessary condition for 
such a state. For that exact reason the development of law can 
be considered a concrete policy towards the strengthening of the 
Russian state". 

</TEXT>

