<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Immediate Release Not Guaranteed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302192494 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1721 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2302192494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] The amnesty resolution does not amount to an 
immediate release of those involved in last October's events, 
sources close to former Vice President Aleksandr Rutskoy told 
Interfax. 
  They say the process may take several months to implement 
despite the resolution's demand for an immediate release of 
Lefortovo prison inmates. 
  One source said the main problem was how to enforce the 
resolution in a legal way. Nor is clear how the Duma's 
constitutional prerogative of declaring amnesties will be 
interpreted, he said. The source says that the amnesty covers 
those convicted but not those under investigation or trial which 
gives a wide room for legal interpretation of the Duma 
resolution. Even if experts arrive at a conclusion that the 
prisoners must be set free immediately, there is always a chance 
of delaying the resolution indefinitely for various reasons such 
as failure to return a book borrowed from the prison library, he 
said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-37901 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov037_b_94010" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-037 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

