<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Yeltsin May Annul Decision </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402125894 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1222 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402125894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 24 TASS--The Russian State Duma 
confused "pardoning" with "amnesty" and thus the Russian 
president may annul its decision to free opposition rebels 
because pardoning is his exclusive right, while the lower 
chamber can only declare an amnesty, according to an aide of the 
Russian leader. 
  "The State Duma replaced the notion of `pardoning' by 
`amnesty' thus exceeding its authority. According to the 
Russian Constitution pardoning is the right of the president", 
national security aide Yuriy Baturin told TASS on Thursday. 
  He explained that there is a big difference between 
"pardoning" and "amnesty". An amnesty frees people convicted 
for certain crimes, while only concrete people can be pardoned. 
  Baturin also said that the Duma decision is contradicting 
the 
principles of law because "there are dead bodies while there are 
nobody guilty". He was referring to over 140 killed during the 
October revolt and the policeman killed during the May Day 
demonstration last year. 
  He stressed that the principle of power sharing between 
authorities had also been violated as, according to the 
Constitution, it is only the court which can decide whether 
defendants are guilty or not. "Thus it would be better to wait 
with pardoning until a court verdict", Baturin said. 
  The national security aide believes the Constitutional Court 
could have helped in the dispute. "But as the law on its 
activities has not been adopted yet, the president, as the 
guarantor of the Constitution has the right to demand that the 
office of the prosecutor general and heads of departments do not 
fulfill the resolution of the State Duma which does not abide by 
the principles of the Constitution and Russian laws", Baturin 
said. 
  He added that the Russian prosecutor general may file a 
protest against the Duma decision which, according to the law, 
is to be considered by the lower chamber. 
  In Baturin's personal opinion the Duma decision was "a 
political-emotional act, rather that a juridical step". 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-37902 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov037_b_94011" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-037 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kostikov Terms Amnesty `Immoral' </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402092494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 0902 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402092494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Anna Melnikova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 24 TASS--Russian President Boris 
Yeltsin will react calmly to the Duma decision to pardon his 
opponents, according to presidential spokesman Vyacheslav 
Kostikov. 
  "The president will react calmly, without emotions. He will 
give a moral assessment of the event", Vyacheslav Kostikov told 
reporters on Thursday. 
  However, the spokesman himself believes the implementation 
of 
the Duma decision would result in "a serious destabilisation", 
will be detrimental to Russian national interests and will 
affect the foreign policy. 
  Kostikov hinted that the amnesty to rebels may not be 
implemented because of a "possible war of juridical 
interpretations". 
  "If the Constitution says that the State Duma declares 
amnesty it does not mean that it adopts a decision on it", 
Kostikov said adding that "the amnesty in its political part is 
immoral" because it frees those who are responsible for the 
death of people. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-37903 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov037_b_94012" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-037 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Kostikov: Decision `Hastily' Adopted </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302181794 Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service in Russian 1729 
GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>

<F P=103> LD2302181794 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS World Service </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Moscow, 23 February -- The decision of the State 
Duma on granting amnesty to the members of the SCSE [State 
Committee for the State of Emergency] and those involved in the 
October 1993 events is a challenge to Russian democracy. The 
feelings of the millions of Russians who defended democracy in 
August 1991 and in October 1993 have been trampled on. In 
initiating the adoption of this decision the Communists and 
supporters of Zhirinovskiy displayed a total unity of aims of 
getting into power by a destabilization of the situation. This 
is said in a statement issued by Vyacheslav Kostikov, the 
Russian president's press secretary. 
  There is no doubt that this decision will harm cooperation 
between the branches of power and the very idea of law and order 
because it elevates a resolution of the issue of the guilt of 
those involved in both coups from the legal to the political 
sphere. This decision is of a purely political nature -- it was 
adopted hastily, without taking the account of public opinion 
and without a preliminary research into the legal foundations 
for adopting and implementing such serious decisions. 
  At the time when the Russian president is taking decisive 
steps to reaffirm Russia's prestige and dignity in the world, 
the State Duma is making decisions which will lead to 
destabilization, and consequently, to the weakening of Russia. 
This path is dangerous and it goes against national interests. 
All the responsibility for the consequences of the adopted 
decision lies with the State Duma, and with those who initiated 
and carried out this action, the statement of the Russian 
president's press secretary says. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

