<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Amnesty Prelude to Reconciliation </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402151694 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1145 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402151694 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] According to the leader of Russian Communists, 
Gennadiy Zyuganov, political amnesty should become the prelude 
to nation-wide reconciliation. He declared this in his 
interview with Interfax in the Kremlin on Thursday. 
  He believes that a civil war "has been going on in Russia 
for 
a long time already," thousands of killed, millions of refugees, 
more than 15 Mn people with incomes far below the subsistence 
minimum are victims of this war. 
  In connection with this, Zyuganov pointed to the following 
historical parallel -- after the civil war of 1917-1920, 
national reconciliation in Russia took place only in 1941 when 
"the people willy-nilly had to struggle for their survival." 
Zyuganov believes that "today the situation is reminiscent of 
this historical parallel." 
  Zyuganov pointed out that the president and government 
should 
express their point of view regarding the amnesty. "This is not 
an issue about which only press secretaries can speak," he noted. 
  Zyuganov believes that liberation of the participants of the 
August 1991 and October 1993 events "will not bring any sharp 
destabilization into the nation's political life." "As a matter 
of fact, such people as Lukyanov, Kryuchkov, that is, people who 
enjoy a great political reputation, and are quite experienced, 
have been freed and they are productively working in Russia's 
favor," he said. 
  "We rule out the notion of "revenge" as a political term," 
noted Zyuganov. A State Duma deputy Aleksandr Nevzorov, a 
prominent TV journalist, who was nearby, declared: "We have 
granted amnesty not only to those who participated in the 1991 
and 1993 events on both sides but by means of this act we have 
granted amnesty to Yeltsin himself." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

