<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Amnesty Vote `Challenge' to President </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302142194 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1414 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2302142194 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Tamara Zamyatina] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 23 TASS -- The decision of the 
Russian State Duma to declare amnesty to anti-Yeltsin rebels on 
the eve of the presidential address to parliament is "an open 
symbolic challenge" to the president, according to Emil Pain, an 
aide of the Russian leader, who added that Yeltsin would not 
approve the decision. 
  The amnesty "puts a constructive dialogue (between the 
president and the parliament) under big doubt", Pain told TASS 
on Wednesday adding that it would not promote stability in 
society either. 
  However, he stressed that the Duma decision should not 
postpone the presidential address as it is a message "not only 
to the Federal Assembly, but to the whole society". 
  On Wednesday the Duma overwhelmingly voted to declare an 
amnesty to organisers of the 1991 Soviet coup, of the armed 
opposition revolt in Moscow last year and of the hard-line 
demonstration in May 1993. All the three events resulted in 
bloodshed. 
  Pain, who is a member of the Presidential Council, regretted 
that the faction headed by Sergey Shakhray also voted to pardon 
the rebels. "It is regretful that the amnesty for political 
adventurists was supported by the faction with the name of 
"Russian Unity and Accord". 

</TEXT>

