<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Political Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Zhirinovskiy, Others React </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302172294 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1537 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2302172294 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [by ITAR-TASS correspondent Lyudmila Aleksandrova] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 23 TASS -- Russian nationalist 
leader Vladimir Zhirinovskiy was brief in assessing the Duma 
decision to pardon anti-Yeltsin rebels on Wednesday. 
  "This is a historic moment. February 23, 1994 means an end 
to civil war in Russia", he told reporters. 
  However, a leader of another major Duma faction is of a 
completely opposite opinion. Sergey Yushchenkov of the Russia's 
Choice said the amnesty to rebels means "the beginning of a 
civil war in Russia". 
  Yegor Gaydar, the leader of the faction, said the decision 
was a move towards destabilisation and warned that the freed 
rebels would return to their activities which would result in a 
new bloodshed. "I am completely convinced that they would work 
so that new blood is shed", he said. 
  According to Gaydar, the president cannot veto the Duma 
decision. 
  Other Duma factions were somewhere in between the radical 
points of view of Russia's Choice and Zhirinovskiy's party. 
  Sergey Stankevich from the Party of Russian Unity and Accord 
said that Russia has got a chance for reconciliation, but warned 
that "it is hard to predict how the chance would be used". 
  Leader of Russian Communists Gennadiy Zyuganov told TASS 
that 
he has a "feeling of certain satisfaction" as agreement has been 
reached among most Duma factions. The Russia's Choice remained 
alone "and began to immediately intimidate by provocations", he 
said. 
  Vladimir Lysenko from the "Yabloko" bloc abstained from the 
vote. He told TASS that it was very tempting to vote for 
universal pardoning, however "if a considerable part of 
extremists is freed this can destabilise the situation". 

</TEXT>

