<DOCNO> FBIS3-37924 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov037_b_94034" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-037 </AU>
Document Type:Daily Report 
<DATE1>  24 Feb 1994 </DATE1>

</HEADER>

<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Seeks Decrease in Troops Abroad </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302174994 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1700 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2302174994 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Vladimir Gondusov] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 23 TASS -- President Boris Yeltsin 
said on Wednesday that Russia wants to minimise the number of 
its troops which are acting as peace-keepers in war-hit regions. 
  "We are worried for our guys and adopt all political and 
diplomatic measures so that there are as few Russian troops 
abroad as possible", Yeltsin said during a meeting with Moscow 
teenagers studying in military schools. 
  The Russian Army would become in the coming years a "mobile, 
well-organised (force), equipped with latest weapons and 
armaments and with highly professional personnel", according to 
the president. 
  Yeltsin called to accelerate the reform in the Armed Forces 
which he said is going not actively enough. 
  He said that the structure of the Armed Forces would be 
considerably changed. The number of major units and formations 
will be reduced, while the remaining ones will be reinforced 
with personnel and modern weapons and hardware. 
  "Only in this case they (units) will be able to localise any 
conflicts", the president said. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

