<F P=100> RUSSIA NATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<F P=101> Military &amp; Nuclear Issues </F>
<H3> <TI>   Says Republics Lack Proper Army </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302200594 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1406 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2302200594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Russian Defense Minister Pavel Grachev told a 
meeting of veterans and servicemen in Moscow Wednesday [23 
February] that none of the former Soviet republics had a proper 
army. He attributed this to shortage of skilled men and absence 
of command structures or deployment systems. This is the reason 
why Russia has undertaken to send troops on peacekeeping 
missions to `hot spots' in the former USSR. "There are numerous 
Russians residing in conflict areas and we must protect their 
interests," the minister said. 
  He said that the reform of the Russian armed forces had run 
into problems in terms of the financing and construction of 
homes for servicemen. He hoped nevertheless, that the compact 
and mobile forces that are required by the new military doctrine 
would be set up. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

