<H3> <TI>   Navy Denies Captured Sub Not From Pacific Fleet </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2402130494 Moscow ITAR-TASS in English 1241 GMT 24 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2402130494 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ITAR-TASS </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [By ITAR-TASS correspondent Sergey Ostanin] </F>
  [Text] Moscow February 24 TASS--The Russian Navy denied 
reports that a nuclear submarine from the Kamchatka flotilla of 
the Pacific Fleet had been netted by a Russian seiner 10 miles 
off the coast of the peninsula on Sunday. 
  "Submarines of the Pacific Fleet have nothing to do with the 
incident near the coast of the Kamchatka Peninsula", the press 
service of the Russian Navy told TASS on Thursday. 
  According to the military, only one nuclear submarine of the 
Kamchatka flotilla was at sea during the time. After its return 
to the base representatives of the company which owes the 
fishing vessel checked the U-boat and did not find either the 
net or any traces of damage. Besides, a detailed investigation 
which also studied the submarine's register and other documents 
confirmed that the U-boat was not involved in the incident. 
  The Kamchatka-based VESTI newspaper reported on Wednesday 
that the Russian "Kamsudo-3" seiner had netted a nuclear 
submarine which safely escaped together with the net worth 20 
million roubles. 
  The ship mistook the submarine for a big shoal of fish. The 
submarine turned out to be right under the fishing vessel and 
had it surfaced there would have been a shipwreck. 
  Astonished fishermen watched the surfaced conning tower of 
the U-boat pass along their vessel and disappear together with 
the net, the newspaper said. 
  It added that this was the second incident of the type. The 
first one was registered in 1976. 
  Now it remains to clear up who the submarine belonged to. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

