<F P=100> Federal Assembly </F>
<H3> <TI>   Duma Approves Resolution on Agriculture </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  LD2302204894 Moscow INTERFAX in English 1721 GMT 23 Feb 94 </F>
<F P=103> LD2302204894 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow INTERFAX </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> English </F>
Article Type:BFN 

  [Text] Aleksandr Nazarchuk, head of the Agrarian Committee 
of the State Duma, the lower house of the Russian parliament, 
said on Wednesday that the draft government resolution "The 
Economic Conditions for the Functioning of the Agroindustrial 
Complex of the Russian Federation in 1994" was signed late on 
Tuesday night. The document caused disagreements at a February 
3 government presidium meeting. 
  Nazarchuk said at a news briefing that Russia's agrarian 
sector had this year received a credit of only 270 Bn rubles at 
213 percent interest. Altogether the sector is to receive under 
the government resolution "five trillion rubles instead of the 
six trillion necessary to carry through the spring sowing and 
end the wintering of the livestock," he said. 
  The agroindustrial complex demanded a credit of 14 to 15 Tn 
rubles for this year, and those were the figures indicated in 
the original version of the resolution, Nazarchuk said. But in 
the version signed on Tuesday all the figures are much lower, he 
said. 
  Vyacheslav Zvolinskiy, chairman of the Agrarian Policy 
Committee of the Federation Council, the upper house of the 
legislature, in this connection expressed skepticism about "the 
hopes of the Ministry of Agriculture and Food to produce 85 Mn 
tonnes of grain this year" (Russia produced 100 Mn tonnes last 
year and 106 Mn tonnes in 1992). He does not expect this year's 
harvest to top 60 or 70 Mn tonnes, "which would last Russia 180 
to 200 days, and then it will be living on doles." 
  Zvolinskiy said Federation Council deputies might propose a 
vote of confidence in the government if it did not change its 
agricultural policy. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

<DOC>
<DOCNO> FBIS3-37936 </DOCNO>
<HT>    "drsov037_c_94005" </HT>


<HEADER>
<AU>   FBIS-SOV-94-037 </AU>
