<H3> <TI>   Move To New Premises Set for Fall </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  PM2302145594 Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA in Russian 23 Feb 94 
First Edition p 1 </F>

<F P=103> PM2302145594 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow ROSSIYSKAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Unattributed report under "In the State Duma" rubric: </F>
"Parliament Changes Address"] 
  [Text] By fall the State Duma will move to its permanent 
residence -- a complex of buildings along the capital's Okhotnyy 
Ryad thoroughfare and Georgiyevskiy Pereulok. Repairs are under 
way in these buildings to replace old fire-hazardous partitions. 
This was reported in an interview with ITAR-TASS correspondents 
by Sergey Filatov, leader of the Russian President's 
Administration. In his opinion "the Russian Federation 
president's edict has written the final chapter in the epic of 
the State Duma's accommodations." 
  The lower house of parliament will be temporarily 
accommodated in the Russian Management Academy in the 
southwestern part of the capital. The president's 
administration has counterarguments against protests from the 
Russian Management Academy collective. The point is that the 
audit carried out by the Control Administration under the 
Russian Federation president revealed numerous infringements of 
tax discipline by the Russian Management Academy leadership. 
Thus, numerous commercial structures which rent the academy's 
premises are either not officially registered at all or do not 
pay taxes to the state budget. 
  As is known, under the Russian Federation president's edict 
the Russian Management Academy will move to the parliamentary 
center building on Tsvetnoy Bulvar. 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

