<F P=100> RUSSIA INTERNATIONAL AFFAIRS </F>
<H3> <TI>   Russian `Success' Viewed </TI></H3>
<F P=102>  MK2402084094 Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA in Russian 24 Feb 94 
p 1 </F>

<F P=103> MK2402084094 </F>
<F P=104>  Moscow NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA </F>


<TEXT>
Language: <F P=105> Russian </F>
Article Type:BFN 

<F P=106> [Andrey Streletskiy report under the "Secret Services" </F>
rubric: "High-Ranking CIA Official, Who Worked for Soviet Union 
and Russia, Arrested. His Recruitment and Long-Time Work May 
Undoubtedly Be Recognized as Domestic Intelligence Service's 
Success"] 
  [Excerpt] [passage omitted] The press bureau of the 
Russian Foreign Intelligence Service [FIS] would not give 
official comments on the arrest of Aldrich Hazen Ames. A 
"no-comment" response in such cases means an indirect 
recognition of an uncovered agent's cooperation with one secret 
service or another. An informed intelligence expert, who asked 
not to be identified, answering your NEZAVISIMAYA GAZETA 
correspondent's question whether this incident is the FIS' worst 
setback recently, said: "I would look at the incident from a 
different side and I would say as follows: The fact that our 
intelligence service has had such an agent for such a long time 
is undoubtedly a great success. Undoubtedly, he was worth the 
great amount of money that was paid to him. The situation 
should not be dramatized and the scandals should not be blown 
out of proportion. No one has yet canceled intelligence 
activity after all. Our agents do in the United States just 
what theirs do here, nothing more. As a matter of fact, when we 
catch their spies we do not demand that their diplomats be 
expelled. It would be most unwelcome if this episode causes 
tension in Russian-American relations. The United States needs 
us just as we need them." 

</TEXT>

</DOC>

